  "final_analysis": "Pneumonia caused by Pneumocystis jirovecii, previously known as P. carinii, is a common opportunistic infection in immunocompromised individuals, particularly those with HIV/AIDS. The standard treatment for this type of pneumonia is Cotrimoxazole (Trimethoprim-Sulfamethoxazole), which is effective against Pneumocystis jirovecii. This is well-established in medical guidelines and literature. Penicillin is not effective as PJP is not caused by bacteria. Kanamycin and Levofloxacin are also not suitable as they do not target the organism responsible for PJP. Therefore, based on standard medical knowledge and consensus, Cotrimoxazole is the drug of choice for treating Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia.",
